@unemployed
subtitle: This demographic once used to be one of the strongest ones, but as expected, widespread employement sadly wipes out unemployement.

Once upon a time, the SPD enjoyed its role as a defender of the unemployed and of Weltkrieg veterans, our unemployement insurance programme even being a notorious example of positive SPD policy. However, the economic boom and golden era that we are living in has largely weakened the size of this demographic, as well as the related effects. Worse yet, conservative media has actively portrayed people who struggle to find permanent work as lazy or as a burden to society. We must regain momentum among this demographic.

This is not to say we have lost support among them. 

- @leech: Well, the problem is how we need more unemployed people. Let's examine what methods we'll have to run unemployement-increasing campaigns?
- @poster: We must try to share the stories of those who were forgotten by the system and try to break the perception that we are in a 'golden age'.
- @veterans: Our focus must be on appealing directly to the veterans of the Weltkrieg. Securing their support will solidify the SPD as a party of the people.
- @mutual_aid: The SPD can make a real change here. Focus on campaigns that bring the unemployed into party organisations, such as nursery care, health services, self-help groups for mental health and rifle clubs.
- @economic_change: We will focus on proposing economic change that will create jobs and change lives.
- @welfare: Let's focus on reiterating our role in the creation of a welfare state that will take care of all.
- @start: Let's check the other demographics.

@leech
subtitle: You can't be serious about this...

Well, chairman, you'll have a very hard time convincing the party of your unemployement increase programme, but here are the main ways we can get it done...

- @pensions: Create a "party pension fund", and give unemployed, injured or old people access to pensions, thus possibly indirectly allowing them to quit their jobs.
- @cheques_lite: Direct Party Funding to writers or intellectuals who are trapped in companies, so that they can quit their jobs and will hopefully make good art about the SPD.
- @cheques: Direct Party Funding towards giving certain workers who fit into some conditions we want (e.c single or homeless) willing to quit their jobs, then we fund their lifestyle.
- @buyout: Let's purchase businesses just to collapse them, thus artificially increasing unemployment.
- @state: Can we start pushing for policies that will deliberately raise unemployment?
- @unemployed: Actually, I changed my mind.

@pensions
subtitle: We'll have to choose who exactly we want to give the pensions to, but this can be much easier to justify compared to any other alternative, given our existing mutual aid network.

